<div>
  <p>
  A <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caesar_cipher">Caesar cipher</a> is one of the oldest and 
  most widely known encryption techniques. It's a type of substitution cipher in which each 
  letter is replaced by a different letter a set number of positions away in the alphabet. 
  <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36xNpbosfTY">For example</a>, with a right shift of 3, 
  "D" becomes "G", and "L" becomes "O".
  </p>
  <p>
  Below, you can enter text that you want to encrypt using the Caesar cipher and then the shift
  that you want to apply. To apply a right shift, enter a positive number; to apply a left shift, 
  enter a negative number. The number that you enter can be greater than 26 to cycle through the
  alphabet more than once.
  </p>
</div>
